<DOC><DOCNO>WSJ910208-0037</DOCNO><DOCID>910208-0037.</DOCID><HL>   International Brief -- Mazda Motor Corp.:   Japanese Auto Concern Cuts   Exports to U.S. by 8,000</HL><DATE>02/08/91</DATE><SO>WALL STREET JOURNAL (J), PAGE A8</SO><CO>   J.MZD</CO><IN>AUTOMOBILES (AUT)INTERNATIONAL TRADE NEWS (TRD)</IN><LP>   Mazda Motor Corp. decided to lower its planned exports tothe U.S. by 8,000 units for the remainder of the year endingMarch 31, a spokesman for the Japanese auto company said.   Production levels both in Japan and the U.S. will remainunchanged for the time being, with the vehicles originallyintended for the U.S. being redirected to other markets, hesaid.</LP><TEXT>   &quot;We expect that the Persian Gulf war will probably havesome effect on the Middle East and U.S. markets,&quot; thespokesman said. He noted that the plan to lower exports tothe U.S. is open to study. &quot;We'll continue to watch the stateof things&quot; in the war, the U.S. economy and the automobilemarkets, he said.   Mazda originally planned to export about 290,000 units tothe U.S. in fiscal 1991, compared with roughly 300,000 unitsin fiscal 1990, the spokesman said. In the U.S., Mazdaproduced about 155,000 units in calendar 1990, he said.</TEXT></DOC>